Intensive Care Unit (ICU) stays in hospitals in the USA dataset

Data included in this dataset was obtained from adults who were admitted to ICU for a wide variety of reasons. Stays less than 48 hours in the ICU were not included in the dataset. All numeric variables in the dataset relate to the first 24 hours of admission to the ICU.

Below is an exploratory data analysis which was conducted prior to constructing a model used to predict outcomes (survival vs death) and a model to explain the relationships between important variables and the risk of death for ICU patients in hospitals in the USA.

There were 2061 unique patients who contributed to the data set, 1148 (56%) were male and the average age was 67 (IQR: 52 - 78) years old.

297 of the patients died during their hospital admission.

ICUs were categorised into four different types.

Factors that may be important predictors of survival in an ICU

Literature review indicates that patients of older age are much more likely to die in an ICU hospital.

As logistic regression models are based on several assumptions including the assumption of no multicollinearity, which states predictor variables should not be highly correlated with each other, only one of each related numeric variable should be considered for included in the model. Therefore, it is important to determine not only if the numeric measure has a significant effect on the ICU survival outcome, but also which of the related variables is the most representative of this effect and should be included as a predictor.

Research has demonstrated that elevated levels of Albumin, AST, Bilirubin, BUN, Creatinine, GCS, Glucose, HCO3, Lactate, respiratory rate and urine output are significant indicators of survival outcome in an ICU. Hence, the maximum variables of these clinical measures may be potential predictors. On the other hand, sudden large changes in heart rate, sodium, pH, temperature and non-invasive systolic blood pressure have been found to have a strong association with ICU survival outcomes. Hence, the difference values of these variables may be more suitable as predictors.

The above plots show difference in the distribution between death and survival of patients during their hospital admission. These are a useful visual representation of which variables may be important for inclusion in our prediction model, where there is moderate difference means and IQRs between survivors and those who died.

A notable difference in the distribution of age by outcome was identified, indicating this variable may be a useful predictor for survival status. Whereas, height and gender plots suggest they may not be useful predictors for survival. may want to consider if gender by age does have a difference in outcome.

Given no evidence has been identified in the literature to suggest height impacts survival outcome, this has not been included in our predictors.

The stacked bar plot for ICU type showed notably different proportions of survivors/in-hospital deaths per ICU type, with a significantly higher chance of survival in the cardiac surgery recovery unit, suggesting it may have some value as a predictor.

Part B: Explanatory survival model

Akaikes Information Criterion (AIC) is useful when comparing models as it takes into account likelihood as well as the number of parameters in the model, which is important to ensure parsimony. As a lower AIC indicates better overall balance between model fit and model simplicity, the reduced multivariable model (coxmodel2) is preferred. This is supported by the likelihood ratio test, which shows that although the maximum log likelihood is larger (i.e.better) for the model 1 (-4254.0) compared to model 2 (-4263.4), the p-value of chisq is not statistically significant (0.1269), indicating that the difference in fit between the two models is not statistically significant and that the simpler multivariable model (coxmodel2) should be chosen.
